SIMPLE: filbert
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: filbert
<hw>fil"bert</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. fr. <ets>fill
+ bread</ets>, as filling the bread or husk; cf. G. <ets>bartnuss</ets>
(lit., bread nut) filbert; or perh. named from a
St.<ets>Philibert</ets>, whose day, Aug. 22, fell in the nutting
season.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The fruit of the
<spn>Corylus Avellana</spn> or <spn>Corylus maxima</spn>, also called
the hazel; the hazelnut. It is an oval nut, containing a kernel that has
a mild, farinaceous, oily taste, agreeable to the palate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In England <xex>filberts</xex> are usually large
hazelnuts, especially the nuts from selected and cultivated trees. The
American hazelnuts are of two other species, <spn>Corylus
Americana</spn> and <spn>Corylus cornuta</spn>, and are also sometimes
called <ex>filberts</ex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The tree bearing the filbert; the
hazelnut tree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Filbert gall</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a gall
resembling a filbert in form, growing in clusters on grapevines. It is
produced by the larva of a gallfly
(<gen>Cecidomyia</gen>).</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Filch</ent>⟦br⟧
